description:
Skate Muties from the 5th Dimension (or SM5D as it was known) was an A5 sized skaters fanzine with a Bristol slant from the 1980s, but it covered so much more - gigs, music, reviews and comic strips.

Edited by 'Bear Hackenbush' with an anarchic twist, SM5D was put together like a serial killers scrapbook. All the text was cut and pasted onto the page with panels from other comics and magazines stuck around the words with new speech bubbles written by the SM5D team, often purile, but always funny.

Shot through the whole thing were comic strips, very much in the style of early Viz, but drawn with real enthusiasm by 'Beano' amongst others. Although there was a definite skateboarding angle, later issues branched out into other areas and paved the way for the follow up zine/comic - Bugs and Drugs in the 1990s, which had a much broader remit.
name: Skate Muties from the Fifth Dimension

description:
After the success of Skate Muties from the Fifth Dimension (or SM5D as it was known), the team took a break before coming back with Bugs and Drugs. This new comic/zine followed the same formula as before but instead of concentrating on skateboarding, the publication covered a much broader spectrum of music and entertainment.

Publication was sporadic, six issues were produced between 1992 and 1995. The first five issues were in the standard UK A5 format (exactly the same size as SM5D), but the final sixth issue was a departure from the norm, with a full-colour cover and a new format (now in the slightly larger american comic book size).

The majority of the artwork (including the wonderful covers) were drawn by an artist called 'Beano'.
name: Bugs and Drugs

description:
Crikey! The Great British Comics Magazine printed 16 issues between 2007 and 2010. It took an in-depth look at British comics, writers and artists. It also included the comic strip 'Hatch' by Glenn B Fleming.

One spin-off special was also printed in April 2008 - Super Spies and Secret Agents.

Although physical publication ceased in 2010, digital specials have since been produced for both Crikey! and Super Spies.
name: Crikey!

description:
Monthly comic reprinting stories from Eagle and the comics that merged with it.

The title lasted for six issues, all published in 1988.

  • Issue 1 - Doomlord and ten Amstor Computer short stories
  • Issue 2 - Thirteenth Floor (reprinting stories from Scream! and Eagle)
  • Issue 3 - Manix (reprinting Manix stories from Eagle issues 79-99)
  • Issue 4 - Death Wish (reprinting stories from Speed) and Manix (reprinting stories from Eagle 100-108)
  • Issue 5 - Doomlord, Manix (reprinting stories from Eagle 109-115) and nine Amstor Computer stories
  • Issue 6 - Bloodfang (reprinting series one) and ten Amstor Computer stories
name: Best of Eagle Monthly
